  "prompt": "What could be the speed of light squared, as per Albert Einstein's theory?",
  "response": "In Albert Einstein's theory of relativity, particularly in the context of his famous equation \\(E = mc^2\\), the term \\(c\\) represents the speed of light in a vacuum. The speed of light is approximately \\(299,792,458\\) meters per second (m/s). When you square this value, you get \\(c^2\\):\n\n\\[\nc^2 \\approx (299,792,458 \\, \\text{m/s})^2 \\approx 8.9875 \\times 10^{16} \\, \\text{m}^2/\\text{s}^2.\n\\]\n\nThis value, \\(8.9875 \\times 10^{16} \\, \\text{m}^2/\\text{s}^2\\), is the speed of light squared. It plays an important role in the equations of relativity, relating energy (E), mass (m), and the speed of light (c).",
